I've gotten a lot of questions about how to clean bones recently. My favorite method is water maceration. It is easy and cheap and I like it because you can put the bones in and forget about them. 
.
There are other methods like anthills, dermestid beetles,  open air, etc, so it's best to explore and find what works best for you. 

🌿🌿🌿PLEASE DO NOT USE BLEACH OR SOAK THEM FOR LONG PERIODS OF TIME IN PEROXIDE. 🌿🌿🌿 it will compromise your bones. It tends to lock in the grease and make them super brittle. Peroxide is the last step and they should only be soaked in diluted peroxide for a few days at the most to whiten them. 
.
I usually change out the water every couple of weeks. Don't add any soap or peroxide to the water. That will kill the bacteria that eats the flesh.
.
Once the bones are free of flesh, then you can start the degreasing bath with dishsoap and water. 
.
Also make sure you know your state and county and laws before scavenging. 
.
.
.

There has been a bit of an uptick in bone and remains sellers and that usually comes with an uprise of the selling of illegal bird skulls. A lot of people do not know of the bird protections in place and they are about as strict as marine protection. If you aren't careful and know what you're selling, you can get hit with heafty fines, a felony and time in jail. 
.
Most birds are protected. These protections, protect all aspects of these birds including feather, eggs and nests.
.
If you sell remains, you have a responsibility to make sure what you are selling is ethical and legal. 
.
Some people have the permits required to possess bird remains such as museums and native tribes, but the vast majority are not allowed to have them so do your due diligence. 
.
.
.
.

you can make the process go faster by heating the water (do not boil!). I'll leave the box in the sun with the lid on or if its cold I will use a fish tank or bathtub heater. 
.
when they are done, rinse them and then you can either leave them as is, dye them or whiten with hydrogen peroxide.

Above ground can be done a bunch of different ways, either with a cage, box with holes drilled in it, shallow burial with something heavy over it etc. If you don't weigh your box down, scavengers might come and steal it.
.
I just started doing the holeless box method by accident and out of a little bit of laziness. I had lost my old box during the move and I didn't feel like making one on the day I found a porcupine. So I did it this way and it worked way better than I could have imagined and there was no stench to deal with since there are no holes for the smell to escape. To me this is the ideal way if you live in the suburbs with neighbors to be considerate of. 
.
The best time to do this is summer, it always takes longer in the colder months, but in the summer there were mountains of flies after just a couple of days and the closed box kept them almost entirely contained so they weren't flying around everywhere. I left it under the box until all of the flies were dead and no more were popping up. I also think the moisture buildup on the inside is key to quick decomp. 
.

I've been scavenging for almost 10 years now and know how difficult it is to get hold of these kinds of specimens (snakes, mink, etc) on your own, especially regularly. Perfectly articulated snake specimens are not easy finds, regular supply of multiple identical skulls in perfect condition. Mink is rarely obtained ethically and mink farms are usually where they come from, same for snakes like these. If one wants to get ahold of them they usually have to purchase them from unethical suppliers especially if they want a constant supply. If you are not seeing proof of where someone is getting their specimens then it's probably too good to be true. 

here is a good idea of what is being marketed towards the bone art community via eBay. It is best to steer clear of these types of pieces when there is no transparency about how they were obtained.

It is the demand for these animals that is driving the market.  Back in 2020, bats were being sold everywhere and the public found out they were being trapped in large numbers across seas and sold to artists. When the secret got out, the demand plummeted, and I rarely see bats anymore, thankfully. There is power where people put their money.
